ce:section.ce:para:
For the in vivo wound healing assessment, representative photos of the animal wounds were taken and those on days 0, 2, 4, 6, and 8 post wound creation (Fig. 4
                        ). Also, the % wound closure compared with day 0 can be seen in Fig. 5
                        . It is obvious that in all cases, from day 2 onwards wound closure improved for wounds treated with the N-doped CNDs. In the wounds treated with a cream containing 1 mg g−1 of N-doped CNDs, wound closure was increased by nearly 10 % between day 2 and 4 and 15 % on day 5, compared with control wounds. Ultimately, the wound was totally closed on day 8. In all cases, control wounds closed on day 12. The application of a cream, containing 2 mg g−1 of N-doped CNDs was proved to be highly effective since wound closure was more increased. On day 2, wound closure was increased by 14 % compared with the control and on days 3, 4, and 5 wound closure was even more increased by 30 %, 28 %, and 23 %, respectively. In addition to the above, visual inspection of the wounds revealed that inflammation was significantly reduced for the N-doped CND-treated wounds, compared with control wounds, validating our previous findings. When a cream containing 4 mg g−1 CNDs was used wound closure was increased by 8–15 % on days 2–5, which was similar to the results obtained with the lowest tested concentration. Overall, it was confirmed that N-doped CNDs from citric acid can be used to promote wound healing, since up to 30 % faster healing could be achieved on the first days of the wound.
